univariate analysis on Reviews columns¶

  1. max reviews is 9992

  2. there are total 596 apps with lowest review in the dataset

  3. there are total 29 categories with lowest review in the dataset

  4. BUSSINESS category is the most number of lowest review in the dataset

  5. ART_AND_DESIGN is the category with less number of lowest number

  6. Their is one outlier in the Reviews column Review is given '3.0M' which is possible but rest of the information in that column is not possible like rating should be under 5 and this row rating 19 which is not possible with the rest of the values in the reviews columns this only contains one row so we can drop this row

    -Error

    • THE reviews table is object type and it should be integer type for feature engineering on that column
    • there is also one error in the reviews columns there is one outlier named '3.0M' and rest of the values are in number format so while changing the datatype we will get an error that string cannot be changed because their is 'M' in the string
    • SO the solution is we can drop that row

def size_apps(x):
  '''
  This function groups the size of an app 
  between ~0 to 100 MB into certain intervals.
  '''
  try:
    if x < 1:
      return 'Below 1'
    elif x >= 1 andxr <10:
      return '1-10'
    elif x >= 10 and x <20:
      return '10-20'
    elif x >= 20 and x <30:
      return '20-30'
    elif x >= 30 and x <40:
      return '30-40'
    elif x >= 40 and x <50:
      return '40-50'
    elif x >= 50 and x <60:
      return '50-60'
    elif x >= 60 and x <70:
      return '60-70'
    elif x >= 70 and x <80:
      return '70-80'
    elif x >= 80 and x <90:
      return '80-90'
    else:
      return '90 and above'
  except:
    return x
